{{Infobox play | name =I Am Thomas: A Brutal Comedy with Songs | image =I Am Thomas.jpg |image_upright=1.25 | caption = | writer = | chorus = | characters = | mute = | setting =[[Edinburgh]] 1696 and Present Day | premiere ={{Start date|df=yes|2016|02|24}} | place =[[Liverpool Playhouse]] | orig_lang =[[English language|English]] | series = | subject =[[Thomas Aikenhead]] | genre = }}
'''''I Am Thomas: A Brutal Comedy with Songs''''' is a [[play (theatre)|play]] based around the death of [[Thomas Aikenhead]], the last person to be hanged for [[blasphemy]] in [[United Kingdom|Britain]]. The play received its world premiere at the [[Liverpool Playhouse]], in February 2016, before embarking on a short [[United Kingdom|UK]] tour. It is a co-production between Told by an Idiot, the [[National Theatre of Scotland]] and the [[Royal Lyceum Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2016/feb/17/i-am-thomas-aikenhead-play-told-by-an-idiot-simon-armitage-blasphemy | title=Simon Armitage on his comedy about the last man hanged for blasphemy | publisher=[[The Guardian]] | work=theguardian.com | date=17 February 2016 | accessdate=20 February 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/arts_ents/14374223.Theatre_that_minds_your_language/?ref=twtrec | title=Theatre that minds your language | publisher=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]] | work=heraldscotland.com | date=22 March 2016 | accessdate=22 March 2016}}</ref>
==Production history== [[File:I Am Thomas cast.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Iain Johnstone in ''I Am Thomas'']] ''I Am Thomas: A Brutal Comedy with Songs'' is a [[devised theatre]] play<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/whats-on/theatre-news/watch-am-thomas-liverpool-playhouse-10908199 | title=Told by an Idiot tells the story of the last man hanged for blasphemy | publisher=[[Liverpool Echo]] | work=liverpoolecho.co.uk | date=18 February 2016 | accessdate=20 February 2016}}</ref> created by Told by an Idiot,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/arts/firstnightreviews/article4699189.ece | title=I Am Thomas at Liverpool Playhouse | publisher=[[The Times]] | work=thetimes.co.uk | date=25 February 2016 | accessdate=26 February 2016}}</ref> based on the real life story of [[Thomas Aikenhead]], a student from [[Edinburgh]] who was prosecuted and executed at the age of 20 on a charge of [[Blasphemy law in the United Kingdom|blasphemy]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/culture/theatre/i-am-thomas-a-timely-adaptation-of-a-17th-century-blasphemy-execution-1-4080181 | title=I Am Thomas, a timely adaptation of a 17th century blasphemy execution | publisher=[[The Scotsman]] | work=scotsman.com | date=23 March 2016 | accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> He was executed at [[Leith Walk|Gallow Lee]] in [[Edinburgh]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.edinburghnews.scotsman.com/news/entertainment/preview-i-am-thomas-a-tale-from-edinburgh-s-dark-past-1-4078953 | title=I Am Thomas, a tale from Edinburgh’s dark past | publisher=[[Edinburgh Evening News]] | work=edinburghnews.scotsman.com | date=22 March 2016 | accessdate=22 March 2016}}</ref> in 1697 and was the last person in [[Great Britain|Britain]] to be executed for blasphemy.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/whats-on/theatre-news/review-am-thomas-liverpool-playhouse-10938898 | title=I Am Thomas at the Liverpool Playhouse | publisher=[[Liverpool Echo]] | work=liverpoolecho.co.uk | date=24 February 2016 | accessdate=22 March 2016}}</ref> Told through the medium of song, the play is set in Edinburgh between 1696 and present day. On 14 April 2015, it was announced by The [[Royal Lyceum Theatre]], that the play would form part of the 50th anniversary season of the Royal Lyceum Theatre company.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://lyceum.org.uk/press/entry/the-lyceum-announces-50th-anniversary-season | title=The Lyceum Announces 50th Anniversary Season! | publisher=[[Royal Lyceum Theatre]] | work=lyceum.org.uk | date=14 April 2015 | accessdate=28 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.list.co.uk/article/70015-brian-cox-and-bill-paterson-return-to-lyceum-for-50th-anniversary-season/ | title=Brian Cox and Bill Paterson return to Lyceum for 50th anniversary season | publisher=[[The List (magazine)|The List]] | work=list.co.uk | date=14 April 2015 | accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref> It is a co-production between Told by an Idiot, the [[National Theatre of Scotland]] and the [[Royal Lyceum Theatre]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/arts_ents/14340362.A_thoroughly_modern_travesty_of_18th_century_justice__Review_of_I_Am_Thomas/ | title=A thoroughly modern travesty of 18th-century justice | publisher=[[Sunday Herald]] | work=heraldscotland.com | date=13 March 2016 | accessdate=23 March 2016}}</ref> ''I Am Thomas'' received its world premiere at the [[Liverpool Playhouse]] on 24 February 2016, following previews from 19 February, for a limited run until 27 February.<ref name="Anderson">{{cite web | url=https://www.thestage.co.uk/reviews/2016/i-am-thomas-review-at-liverpool-playhouse-emotionally-charged/ | title=Told By An Idiot takes gallows humour literally in this new musical production | publisher=[[The Stage]] | work=thestage.co.uk | date=25 February 2016 | accessdate=26 February 2016}}</ref>
The play is directed by Paul Hunter, Artistic Director of Told by an Idiot,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2016/feb/28/i-am-thomas-review-thomas-aikenhead-simon-armitage | title=I Am Thomas review – freedom of speech theatrics | publisher=[[The Guardian]] | work=theguardian.com | date=28 February 2016 | accessdate=16 March 2016}}</ref> with design by Laura Hopkins,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wirralglobe.co.uk/news/14302479.HOT_OFF_THE_STAGE___I_Am_Thomas__at_Liverpool_Playhouse/ | title='I Am Thomas' at Liverpool Playhouse | publisher=Wirral Globe | work=wirralglobe.co.uk | date=25 February 2016 | accessdate=26 February 2016}}</ref> lighting design by Paul Anderson,<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/edinburgh-theatre/shows/i-am-thomas_84383/cast/ | title=I Am Thomas Company | publisher=Whats On Stage | work=whatsonstage.com | accessdate=24 March 2016}}</ref> music by Iain Johnstone,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2016/feb/26/i-am-thomas-review-told-by-an-idiot-liverpool-playhouse | title=I Am Thomas review – singalong-a-blasphemy in Simon Armitage show | publisher=[[The Guardian]] | work=theguardian.com | date=26 February 2016 | accessdate=26 February 2016}}</ref> lyrics by [[Simon Armitage]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/theatre/what-to-see/i-am-thomass-brutal-comedy-is-a-bold-theatrical-experiment/ | title=I Am Thomas's brutal comedy is a bold theatrical experiment | publisher=[[The Daily Telegraph|The Telegraph]] | work=telegraph.co.uk | date=26 February 2016 | accessdate=26 February 2016}}</ref> and sound by Adrienne Quartly.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.nationaltheatrescotland.com/content/mediaassets/pdf%5C/I%20AM%20THOMAS%20freesheet.pdf | title=I am Thomas a brutal comedy with songs – UK Tour 2016 | publisher=[[National Theatre of Scotland]] | work=nationaltheatrescotland.com | accessdate=16 March 2016}}</ref> Following its premiere production the play embarked on a short [[United Kingdom|UK]] tour<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.whatsonstage.com/london-theatre/news/national-theatre-of-scotland-announce-season_39117.html | title=National Theatre of Scotland announce start of 10th anniversary season | publisher=Whats On Stage | work=whatsonstage.com | date=11 November 2015 | accessdate=24 March 2016}}</ref> in March and April 2016, visiting [[The Lowry]], [[Salford, Greater Manchester|Salford]], [[Salisbury Playhouse]], [[Salisbury]], [[Royal Lyceum Theatre]], [[Edinburgh]], Eden Court Theatre, [[Inverness]], and Wilton's Music Hall, London.<ref name="Broadway">{{cite web | url=http://www.broadwayworld.com/uk-regional/article/I-AM-THOMAS-Coming-to-Wiltons-Music-Hall-in-April-20160321# | title=I Am Thomas Coming to Wilton's Music Hall in April | publisher=Broadway World | work=broadwayworld.com | date=21 March 2016 | accessdate=22 March 2016}}</ref> The play features an ensemble cast of eight<ref name = "Broadway"/> who take it in turn to play the title role.<ref name = "Anderson"/> The cast includes John Cobb, Charlie Folorunsho, Amanda Hadingue, Myra McFadyen, Hannah McPake, John Pfumojena,<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.toldbyanidiot.org/productions/i-am-thomas/ | title=I Am Thomas - a brutal comedy with songs Team | publisher=Told By An Idiot | work=toldbyanidiot.org | accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref> [[Dominic Marsh]] and Iain Johnstone who wrote the plays score.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.salisburyjournal.co.uk/news/14315202.Brutal_comedy_with_songs_explores_hidden_piece_of_history/ | title=Brutal comedy with songs explores hidden piece of history | publisher=Salisbury Journal | work=salisburyjournal.co.uk | date=2 March 2016 | accessdate=22 March 2016}}</ref> A typical performance runs two hours, including one [[Entr'acte|interval]] of 20 mins.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://twitter.com/lyceumtheatre/status/715276958775566336 | title=I Am Thomas Run Time | publisher=[[Royal Lyceum Theatre]] | work=twitter.com/lyceumtheatre | accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref>
==Critical reception== The play has received mixed to positive reviews from critics.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.list.co.uk/article/79579-theatre-review-i-am-thomas/ | title=A rhapsody of ill-invented nonsense, patched up partly of the moral doctrines of philosophers, and partly of poetical fictions and extravagant chimeras | publisher=[[The List (magazine)|The List]] | work=list.co.uk | date=29 March 2016 | accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.theartsdesk.com/theatre/i-am-thomas-royal-lyceum-theatre-edinburgh | title=Brutal comedy with songs' on the last man executed for blasphemy is exuberant but confused | publisher=The Arts Desk | work=theartsdesk.com | date=26 March 2016 | accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.scotsman.com/lifestyle/culture/theatre/theatre-review-i-am-thomas-royal-lyceum-theatre-edinburgh-1-4082874 | title=Theatre review: I Am Thomas, Royal Lyceum Theatre, Edinburgh | publisher=[[The Scotsman]] | work=scotsman.com | date=25 March 2016 | accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://heraldscotland.com/arts_ents/14383514.Theatre_review__I_Am_Thomas_at_Royal_Lyceum_Theatre__Edinburgh/ | title=I Am Thomas at Royal Lyceum Theatre, Edinburgh | publisher=[[The Herald (Glasgow)|The Herald]] | work=heraldscotland.com | date=25 March 2016 | accessdate=30 March 2016}}</ref> ==References== {{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}
